A '''leprose lichen''' is a [[lichen]] with a powdery or granular surface.<ref name=ASLTT>[http://www.lichens.lastdragon.org/faq/lichenthallustypes.html#foliose Fioliose lichens, Lichen Thallus Types, Allan Silverside]</ref>  Leprose lichens lack an outer "skin," or [[Cortex (anatomy)|cortex]].<ref name=ASLTT/> If a [[crustose lichen]] starts to disintegrate, it will appear powdery, but crustose lichens will leave a cortex surface, and leprose lichens do not.<ref name=ASLTT/><ref>http://www.earthlife.net/lichens/lichen.html</ref> Leprose lichens have no inner or outer cortex. They sometimes have a weak kind of [[Medulla (lichenology)|medulla]], but are composed mainly of the fungal hyphae and an algae.

